# Primary constructors for commands and records

**Commands and records** (including request/response DTO records, MediatR-style commands, validators that only capture parameters) **may use primary constructors** when they are simple data carriers.

For other types (services, handlers, endpoints, entities with behavior), **prefer explicit constructors** or avoid primary constructors unless the team’s general style rule applies.

## Examples

```csharp
// ✅ OK — command / record-style type
public record CreateBrandCommand(string Name, string ClientId);

public class CreateBrandCommandValidator : AbstractValidator<CreateBrandCommand>
{
    public CreateBrandCommandValidator() { /* FluentValidation rules */ }
}
```

```csharp
// Prefer a normal constructor for handlers and other non-DTO types (no primary constructor)
public class CreateBrandCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreateBrandCommand, string>
{
    private readonly IUnitOfWork _unitOfWork;

    public CreateBrandCommandHandler(IUnitOfWork unitOfWork)
    {
        _unitOfWork = unitOfWork;
    }
}
```
